<div id="tmglBody" >
	<div class="access"><a name="article"></a></div>
		
	<div class="twoThirdsThird2 gutterUnder">
		<div class="twoThirds gutter">
			<div class="storyHead">
	
	<h1>Hay Festival 2011: John Waters on 10 things every role model needs</h1>
		
	<h2>
Words of wisdom from film director John Waters at the Hay Festival. 

</h2>
	<div class="artIntro">
					<div id="storyEmbSlide">
			<div class="slideshow ssIntro">
				<div class="nextPrevLayer">
							<div class="ssImg">
									<img src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/01905/waters1_1905888b.jpg" width="620" height="388" alt="John Waters"/>
									<div class="artImageExtras" >
									
										<div class="ingCaptionCredit">
											<span class="caption">John Waters: 'I think it helps to be neurotic'</span>&nbsp;</div>						
									</div>
								</div>
							</div>			
					</div>
		</div>
		
	</div>	
			</div>
<div class="oneHalf gutter">
				<div class="story">
					<div class="cl"> </div>
	<div class="byline">
		<span class="bylineBody">By John Waters</span>
				
				<span class="publishedDate">7:18PM BST 27 May 2011</span>
		
		<p class="comments">
				<a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/hay-festival/8538942/Hay-Festival-2011-John-Waters-on-10-things-every-role-model-needs.html#disqus_thread" dsqid="8538942">Comments</a>
			</p>
		<div class="cl"> </div>
	</div>
	<div id="mainBodyArea">
<div class="firstPar"><p>
<strong>1. History.</strong> You can&rsquo;t have a one-night-stand role model. No one can 
  become a role model in 24 hours. It helps a lot if you knew them when you 
  were young, so they sort of grow or fester with you, like Johnny Mathis was 
  for me. 
</p></div><div class="secondPar">
<p></p></div><div class="thirdPar">
<p>
<strong>2 Be extreme: </strong>all my role models have to be. They have to be braver 
  than I&rsquo;ve ever been. Even to survive success is hard, no matter if it&rsquo;s 
  widespread success like Johnny Mathis had, or Bobby Boris Pickett, who his 
  whole life just had to sing one song [The Monster Mash]. Today too many 
  people are trying hard to be extreme. For the people I admire it was 
  natural, and they turned it into art. 
</p></div><div class="fourthPar">
<p></p></div><div class="fifthPar">
<p>
<strong>3 Style.</strong> You can have bad style, but you have to have some style. 
  That&rsquo;s why I wrote about Rei Kawakubo, who reinvented fashion to be damaged 
  and to be everything you hoped it was not when you bought an outfit. And she 
  quadrupled the price. That&rsquo;s a magic trick. 
</p></div><!-- BEFORE ACI -->	<div class="body">
<p></p>
<p>
<strong>4 Be alarming</strong> &ndash; I think that&rsquo;s important. And it&rsquo;s different from being 
  shocking. Alarming threatens the very core of your existence, it doesn&rsquo;t 
  just shock you &ndash; but you don&rsquo;t know why it makes you nervous at first. You 
  know, St Catherine of Siena drank pus for God. That was important to me 
  because I thought: I want to be her, I don&rsquo;t want to be half-assed! If I was 
  going to be a Catholic, it would have been before the Reformation. 
</p>
<p></p>
<p>
<strong>5 Humour. </strong>It&rsquo;s very important to be well-read, but I never understand 
  why people are so sure their partners have to be smart. What kind of smart 
  do they mean? I&rsquo;m not interested in talking about literature in bed! I like 
  people who can make me laugh. Humour gets you laid, humour gets you hired, 
  humour gets you through life. You don&rsquo;t get beat up if you can make the 
  person that&rsquo;s going to beat you up laugh first. 
</p>
<p></p>
<p>
<strong>6 Be a troublemaker</strong>. All art is troublemaking, because why go through 
  all the trouble of making it if you don&rsquo;t cause a little stir? 
</p>
<p></p>
<p>
<strong>7 Bohemianism. </strong>Bohemia saved my life. And by bohemia I mean all 
  sexualities mixed together, and people who do what they do not to get rich &ndash; 
  freedom from suburbia. People who want to fit in but don&rsquo;t are losers. 
  Bohemians are people who don&rsquo;t fit in because they don&rsquo;t want to. 
</p>
<p></p>
<p>
<strong>8 Originality.</strong> Someone unique like Margaret Hamilton, the Wicked Witch 
  of the West, is an easy role model to have. She could fit into any of these 
  categories &ndash; her outfit looked like Comme des Gar&ccedil;ons, and anybody who could 
  scare children like that&hellip; The problem was, I wanted to be her. And as I turn 
  65, that has sort of come true. 
</p>
<p></p>
<p>
<strong>9 Neuroses. </strong>I think it helps to be neurotic. Neurotic people always end 
  up being in the arts. If your kid fits in while in high school they&rsquo;re going 
  to be a dull adult. I still see a few people I went to high school with, but 
  the other ones, when they come up to me I say: &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry, I took LSD, I 
  don&rsquo;t remember you.&rdquo; It works, because then they aren&rsquo;t offended personally. 
  It&rsquo;s really just manners. 
</p>
<p></p>
<p>
<strong>10 Be a little bit insane. </strong>That&rsquo;s different from neurotic. You can stay 
  home and be neurotic. You have to go out to be insane. You can be a little 
  bit of both, but both need to be joyous. As long as you can find a moment of 
  joy in even your worst behaviour, it&rsquo;s something to be thankful for. 
</p>
<p></p>
<ul class="storylist">
<li>John Waters has made cult film classics such as Polyester, Cecil B Demented  
      and the global hit Hairspray. He will be discussing his book Role Models 
      on Saturday at the <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/hay-festival/">Hay 
       Festival</a> at 8.30pm</li>
</ul>
</div><div class="cl"></div>
</div></div>
			</div>	
	
